Red Wine Quality Exploration

Bart Leatham

04/18/2017

Wine experts judge wines on a variety of categories in an attempt to quantify a wines quality. One of the categories used is the ‘balance’ of a wine. The balance consists of 4 measureable traits, sweetness, acidity, tannin and alcohol content. While personal taste will always prevail over a wine ‘experts’ opinion, this investigation into a dataset containing the judgments of at least three wine experts will attempt to quantify the relationships between the traits of a balanced wine and the perceived quality rating by the judges. This dataset consists of data related to red Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine.

Source of the dataset

Created by: Paulo Cortez (Univ. Minho), Antonio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida, Telmo Matos and Jose Reis (CVRVV) @ 2009

Attribute Information

1 - fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
2 - volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
3 - citric acid (g / dm^3)
4 - residual sugar (g / dm^3)
5 - chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3
6 - free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
7 - total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
8 - density (g / cm^3)
9 - pH
10 - sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
11 - alcohol (% by volume)
Output variable (based on sensory data):
12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Attribute Descriptions:

1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

I converted the ‘quality’ feature to a factor as it is discrete values, and created a ‘quality.bucket’ variable with low, mid and high quality buckets for more meaningful analysis.
It should be noted, as shown in the summary above, that there are many more datapoints falling in the ‘mid’(1319) quality bucket than ‘low’(63) or ‘high’(217). This should be considered when making any assumptions about the analysis.

Univariate Plots Section

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

1599 obs. of 13 variables. 11 input variables, 2 output variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

This analysis is focused on the balance of the wines, of which the traits are sweetness, acidity, tannin and alcohol. The dataset does not contain a measure for tannins, so the investigation will focus on sweetness (measured by residual.sugar), acidity (measured by pH), the alcohol content and quality rating.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I am curious how the density of the wine will relate to the quality rating.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I bucketed the quality ratings into a quality.bucket variable, with low, med, high being the buckets. This allows for a more meaningful analysis, as the counts for some quality rankings were low compared to others.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

This dataset met tidy data requirements as delivered, so the only cleaning I performed was to remove the X column as it was just a line count index.
Most of the features have an overall normal distribution, some skewed to the right, with a long tail of outliers.

A quick look at the correlation between the variables shows that there are no strong correlations between quality and the various input variables, the strongest postive correlation being the alcohol content at r= 0.48, and the strongest negative correlation being the volatile acidity at r= -0.39.

Bivariate Plots

After perfoming multiple plotting techniques (hist, bar, density, scatter, box) for introductory analysis, I found that using a box plot of each variable vs. quality.bucket yielded the most useful visual data for Bivariate analysis.

Bivariate Analysis

Upon analyzing the above plots, we can see that the higher the chloride and volatile.acidity, the lower the quality.
The higher the fixed.acidity, sulfates, alcohol and citric.acid, the higher the quality.
It is interesting to note, that if relying on the box plots alone, one could infer that the variables mentioned could have a large correlation to the quality of the wine. Since we have looked at the correlation values explicity, we know that this is not case, there is a correlation, though not a strong one.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Of the 4 features of interest, density and alcohol content have the strongest correlations to the quality of the wine. Density has a r = -0.17 while alcohol has r = 0.48 correlation to the quality of the wine. The pH and residual sugar have low correlations (r = -0.06 and r = 0.01 respectively). I expected that the residual sugar would have more of an impact, as I often hear wines described as being too sweet.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

It was interesting to see that the correlation data reinforced some relationships that would be expected. For instance, the various *.acid features have relatively strong correlations to the pH.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship that I found was between free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide. This makes sense, as the free.sulfur.dioxide is a subset of the total.sulfur.dioxide, so it is not particularly interesting.

Multivariate Plots Section

I was interested in looking deeper into the relationships between the residual sugar, density, pH, alcohol content and quality.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Above we can see that higher alcohol levels consistently yield higher quality ranking results.
For residual sugar, we can see that there are no high quality ranked wines with a residual sugar level over ~9g/dm^3, giving credence to some wines being too sweet.
For the pH, we can see that above ~3.75 and below ~2.5 there are no high quality ranked wines, leading me to believe that a pH of 2.5-3.75 is the range for a well balanced wine, not too acidic or basic. It can be noted though, that on the pH scale, that range is quite acidic.
For the density of the wine, we cannot infer much as to quality, we do see correlation to the fact that lower density results in higher alcohol levels, which we have seen have a moderate correlation to quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

## Warning: Removed 125 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Description One

The above plots shows the probability density of each of our traits of interest in investigating the ‘balance’ of our wine observations.
We can see that in isolation, higher alcohol content, lower pH and slightly higher residual sugar lead to higher quality wines.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot shows the relationship between the quality of a wine and the ratio of alcohol/pH. It shows the optimum ratio of alcohol to pH as being 3.5, with a clear differentiation from the optimum ratios for low or mid ranked wines.
This reinforces the fact that wines with a lower pH, and a higher alcohol content are ranked higher in quality in the given dataset.

Plot Three

Description Three

This last plot adresses my additional feature of interest, does the density of the wine effect the quality of the wine? From the plot above we can see that lower density does correlate with a higher quality rating, confirmed by the r = -0.17 found in the correlation section of this investigation. With density having an r = 0.5 correlation to alcohol content, common sense is validated knowing that alcohol has a lower density than water (1g/cm^3), so higher alcohol content lowers the density of the wine.

Reflection

This red wine dataset provided 1599 observations of 11 input and 1 output variable. I first looked into the distribution of the variable values, then moved on to their correlations. Once I saw that the correlations were generally weak, especially with regard to the reported quality rating of the wine, I realized that I needed to come up with a direction to take the investigation. At that point I researched how wine quality is generally defined by experts, and decided to pursue the measure of ‘Balance’ for a wine and investigated its traits as much as possible with the data provided.
The main struggle I faced in this investigation was the fact that none of the independant variables were statistically strongly correlated to the quality ranking of the wines.
I was surprised to see that the features were not more strongly correlated to the quality rating of the wines. Before this investigation I would have guessed that alcohol, pH and sweetness all would have been more highly correlated with the quality rating. To me this proves that wine quality ratings are highly subjective, and a wine consumer would do best to trust their tastebuds (and wallets) over being overly concerned with how a wine expert views their choice. Future work with this dataset I would be interested in having both a measure of tannins, and the price of the wine included. Having the tannin measure available would enable the ability to create a full model of the ‘Balance’ traits. The price data would be an interesting data point to investigate, is the pricing vs quality normally distributed, or does it shift towards higher? It would also be interesting to see a dataset with more varieties of wine, to get a more broad understanding of how the features effect quality, and how the features differ between wine varieties.
